.LP
.nf

.B
error(Reason) -> no_return()
.br
.fi
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Reason = term()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Stops the execution of the calling process with the reason \fIReason\fR\&, where \fIReason\fR\& is any term\&. The exit reason is \fI{Reason, Where}\fR\&, where \fIWhere\fR\& is a list of the functions most recently called (the current function first)\&. As evaluating this function causes the process to terminate, it has no return value\&. Example:
.LP
.nf

> catch error(foobar)\&.
{'EXIT',{foobar,[{shell,apply_fun,3,
                        [{file,"shell.erl"},{line,906}]},
                 {erl_eval,do_apply,6,[{file,"erl_eval.erl"},{line,677}]},
                 {erl_eval,expr,5,[{file,"erl_eval.erl"},{line,430}]},
                 {shell,exprs,7,[{file,"shell.erl"},{line,687}]},
                 {shell,eval_exprs,7,[{file,"shell.erl"},{line,642}]},
                 {shell,eval_loop,3,[{file,"shell.erl"},{line,627}]}]}}

.fi
.RE
.LP
.nf

.B
error(Reason, Args) -> no_return()
.br
.fi
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Reason = term()
.br
Args = [term()]
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Stops the execution of the calling process with the reason \fIReason\fR\&, where \fIReason\fR\& is any term\&. The exit reason is \fI{Reason, Where}\fR\&, where \fIWhere\fR\& is a list of the functions most recently called (the current function first)\&. \fIArgs\fR\& is expected to be the list of arguments for the current function; in Beam it is used to provide the arguments for the current function in the term \fIWhere\fR\&\&. As evaluating this function causes the process to terminate, it has no return value\&.
.RE
.LP
.nf

.B
exit(Reason) -> no_return()
.br
.fi
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Reason = term()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Stops the execution of the calling process with exit reason \fIReason\fR\&, where \fIReason\fR\& is any term\&. As evaluating this function causes the process to terminate, it has no return value\&. Example:
.LP
.nf

> exit(foobar)\&.
** exception exit: foobar
> catch exit(foobar)\&.
{'EXIT',foobar}
.fi
.RE
.LP
.nf

.B
exit(Pid, Reason) -> true
.br
.fi
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
Pid = pid() | port()
.br
Reason = term()
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP
Sends an exit signal with exit reason \fIReason\fR\& to the process or port identified by \fIPid\fR\&\&.
.LP
The following behavior applies if \fIReason\fR\& is any term, except \fInormal\fR\& or \fIkill\fR\&:
.RS 2
.TP 2
*
If \fIPid\fR\& is not trapping exits, \fIPid\fR\& itself exits with exit reason \fIReason\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
If \fIPid\fR\& is trapping exits, the exit signal is transformed into a message \fI{\&'EXIT\&', From, Reason}\fR\& and delivered to the message queue of \fIPid\fR\&\&.
.LP
.TP 2
*
\fIFrom\fR\& is the process identifier of the process that sent the exit signal\&. See also \fB\fIprocess_flag/2\fR\&\fR\&\&.
.LP
.RE

.LP
If \fIReason\fR\& is the atom \fInormal\fR\&, \fIPid\fR\& does not exit\&. If it is trapping exits, the exit signal is transformed into a message \fI{\&'EXIT\&', From, normal}\fR\& and delivered to its message queue\&.
.LP
If \fIReason\fR\& is the atom \fIkill\fR\&, that is, if \fIexit(Pid, kill)\fR\& is called, an untrappable exit signal is sent to \fIPid\fR\&, which unconditionally exits with exit reason \fIkilled\fR\&\&.
.RE
.LP
.nf

.B
erlang:external_size(Term) -> integer() >= 0
