.B
erlang:get_stacktrace() -> [stack_item()]
.br
.fi
.br
.RS
.LP
Types:

.RS 3
.nf
\fBstack_item()\fR\& = 
.br
    {Module :: module(),
.br
     Function :: atom(),
.br
     Arity :: arity() | (Args :: [term()]),
.br
     Location ::
.br
         [{file, Filename :: string()} |
.br
          {line, Line :: integer() >= 1}]}
.fi
.br
.RE
.RE
.RS
.LP

.RS -4
.B
Warning:
.RE
\fIerlang:get_stacktrace/0\fR\& is deprecated and will stop working in a future release\&.

.LP
Instead of using \fIerlang:get_stacktrace/0\fR\& to retrieve the call stack back-trace, use the following syntax:
.LP
.nf

try Expr
catch
  Class:Reason:Stacktrace ->
   {Class,Reason,Stacktrace}
end
.fi
.LP
\fIerlang:get_stacktrace/0\fR\& retrieves the call stack back-trace (\fIstacktrace\fR\&) for an exception that has just been caught in the calling process as a list of \fI{Module,Function,Arity,Location}\fR\& tuples\&. Field \fIArity\fR\& in the first tuple can be the argument list of that function call instead of an arity integer, depending on the exception\&.
.LP
If there has not been any exceptions in a process, the stacktrace is \fI[]\fR\&\&. After a code change for the process, the stacktrace can also be reset to \fI[]\fR\&\&.
.LP
The stacktrace is the same data as operator \fIcatch\fR\& returns, for example:
.LP
.nf

{'EXIT',{badarg,Stacktrace}} = catch abs(x)
.fi
.LP
\fILocation\fR\& is a (possibly empty) list of two-tuples that can indicate the location in the source code of the function\&. The first element is an atom describing the type of information in the second element\&. The following items can occur:
.RS 2
.TP 2
.B
\fIfile\fR\&:
The second element of the tuple is a string (list of characters) representing the filename of the source file of the function\&. 
.TP 2
.B
\fIline\fR\&:
The second element of the tuple is the line number (an integer > 0) in the source file where the exception occurred or the function was called\&. 
.RE
.LP

.RS -4
.B
Warning:
.RE
Developers should rely on stacktrace entries only for debugging purposes\&.
.LP
The VM performs tail call optimization, which does not add new entries to the stacktrace, and also limits stacktraces to a certain depth\&. Furthermore, compiler options, optimizations and future changes may add or remove stacktrace entries, causing any code that expects the stacktrace to be in a certain order or contain specific items to fail\&.
.LP
The only exception to this rule is \fIerror:undef\fR\& which guarantees to include the Module, Function and Arity of the attempted function as the first stacktrace entry\&.

.LP
See also \fB\fIerror/1\fR\&\fR\& and \fB\fIerror/2\fR\&\fR\&\&.
.RE
.LP
.nf

